    "publications": [
      {
        "title": "Conveyor: One-Tool-Fits-All Continuous Software Deployment at Meta",
        "publishedAt": "OSDI (Operating Systems Design & Implementation) · Jul 10, 2023",
        "description": "Abstract:\nWe present Conveyor, Meta's software deployment tool, along with the valuable data obtained from managing over 30,000 deployment pipelines that deploy all kinds of services at Meta across millions of machines. We describe a wide range of deployment scenarios that Conveyor supports to achieve universal coverage. At Meta, out of all the deployment pipelines for services deployed via containers, 97% of them employ fully automated deployments without manual intervention: 55% utilize continuous deployment, instantly deploying every code change to production after passing automated tests, and the remaining 42% are automatically deployed on a fixed schedule (mostly daily or weekly) without manual validation. We highlight several distinguishing features of Conveyor, including safe in-place updates to reduce hardware costs, analysis of code dependencies to prevent faulty releases, and the capability to deploy complex ML models at scale.",
        "link": "https://www.usenix.org/conference/osdi23/presentation/grubic"
      },
      {
        "title": "Global Capacity Management at Meta",
        "publishedAt": "Systems @Scale · Sep 6, 2022",
        "description": "This is the accompanying blog post for my talk at Systems @Scale 2022 Summer.\nVideo: https://atscaleconference.com/videos/global-capacity-management-at-meta/\n\nDescription for the talk:\nMeta currently operates more than 15 data center regions around the world. This rapidly expanding global datacenter footprint poses new challenges for service owners and for our infrastructure management systems. In this talk, we will present the challenges with managing a global-scale infrastructure and our approach for global service and capacity management. In particular, we’ll focus on the abstractions and guarantees we present to service owners with global capacity, and we’ll walk through our current design and implementation for how we manage our workloads across 10s of regions. We’ll also present our future plans with Infra Cloud as we build towards our longer term vision of transparent automated global capacity management.",
        "link": "https://engineering.fb.com/2022/09/06/data-center-engineering/viewing-the-world-as-a-computer-global-capacity-management/"
      },
      {
        "title": "Twine: A Unified Cluster Management System for Shared Infrastructure",
        "publishedAt": "OSDI (Operating Systems Design & Implementation) · Nov 1, 2020",
        "description": "Presentation Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_-K-DeA7n5s\n\nAbstract:\nWe present Twine, Facebook's cluster management system which has been running in production for the past decade. Twine has helped convert our infrastructure from a collection of siloed pools of customized machines dedicated to individual workloads, into a large-scale shared infrastructure with fungible hardware.\n\nOur goal of ubiquitous shared infrastructure leads us to some decisions counter to common practices. For instance, rather than deploying an isolated control plane per cluster, Twine scales a single control plane to manage one million machines across all data centers in a geographic region and transparently move jobs across clusters.\n\nTwine accommodates workload-specific customization in shared infrastructure, and this approach further departs from common practices. The TaskControl API allows an application to collaborate with Twine to handle container lifecycle events, e.g., restarting a ZooKeeper deployment's followers first and its leader last during a rolling upgrade. Host profiles capture hardware and OS settings that workloads can tune to improve performance and reliability; Twine dynamically allocates machines to workloads and switches host profiles accordingly.\n\nFinally, going against the conventional wisdom of prioritizing stacking workloads on big machines to increase utilization, we universally deploy power-efficient small machines outfit with a single CPU and 64GB RAM to achieve higher performance per watt, and we leverage autoscaling to improve machine utilization.\n\nWe describe the design of Twine and share our experience in migrating Facebook's workloads onto shared infrastructure.",
        "link": "https://www.usenix.org/conference/osdi20/presentation/tang"
      },
      {
        "title": "Efficient, reliable cluster management at scale with Tupperware",
        "publishedAt": "Systems @Scale · Jun 6, 2019",
        "description": "This is the accompanying blog post for my talk at Systems @Scale 2019.\nVideo: https://atscaleconference.com/videos/systems-scale-2019-scaling-cluster-management-at-facebook-with-tupperware/\n\nDescription for the talk:\nTupperware is Facebook's cluster management system and container platform, and it has been running in production since 2011. Today, Tupperware manages millions of containers, and almost all backend services at Facebook are deployed through Tupperware. In this talk, we will explore the challenges we encountered over the past eight years as we evolved our system to scale to our global fleet. We will discuss scalability challenges we faced, stateful services and how we support them, our approach for opportunistic compute, and upcoming challenges we are tackling next.",
        "link": "https://code.fb.com/data-center-engineering/tupperware/"
      },
      {
        "title": "End-to-end Deadlock Debugging Tools at Facebook",
        "publishedAt": "CppCon · Sep 29, 2017",
        "description": "Facebook has developed tooling to help quickly find and debug several classes of concurrency bugs in Facebook's large C++ codebase. In this talk, we will focus specifically on deadlocks and the tools we use to detect and prevent them. We will explore the various tools we use — some open source tools we have deployed and some we have developed — and how they work by walking through several examples of real-world bugs found by these tools in Facebook's large production systems. \n\nTopics include: \n* How we deploy and utilize ThreadSanitizer on Facebook's large codebase \n* Linux eBPF tools to detect potential deadlocks on running binaries \n* gdb extensions to examine mutex internals to detect deadlocks \n* folly::Synchronized and other libraries that make it more difficult to introduce concurrency bugs \n\nPresented at CppCon 2017\nVideo: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pz4ILxtPKMs\nSlides and Poster: https://github.com/CppCon/CppCon2017",
        "link": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pz4ILxtPKMs"
      }
